<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israel-Jordan-Egypt System To Monitor Oil Spills </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1901081294 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0700 GMT 19 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1901081294 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Israel, Jordan, and Egypt will establish a joint 
system of installations, equipment, and early-warning units in 
the northern part of the Gulf of Elat to deal with possible oil 
spills in the sea. The early-warning units will be placed in 
three locations -- Elat, 'al-'Aqabah, and al-Nuwaybi' -- and 
will be built with EC financing. The decision to set up the 
joint system was made at a meeting held in al-Nuwaybi' in the 
Sinai by the multinational committee on environment affairs 
within the framework of the peace talks. The systems will be 
built within one to one and a half years 
  (Christian Falkovsky), the EC representative who presided 
over the meetings, told our correspondent Shulamit Schmerling 
that he hopes Saudi Arabia will join the efforts to save the 
environment at a later stage. Our correspondent points out that 
it is estimated that the European financing of the system will 
total $10 to $15 million. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

