<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Assassination Attempt Against Saddam Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1801153094 London THE DAILY TELEGRAPH in English 18 Jan 94 
p 12 </F>

<F P=103> PM1801153094 </F>
<F P=104>  London THE DAILY TELEGRAPH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Gerald Butt report: "Saddam Survives Attack"] </F>
  [Text] Nicosia -- President Saddam Husayn has survived 
another attempt on his life -- the third since last 
summer-according to a highly placed Iraqi official. 
  The official said in the Jordanian capital, Amman, that a 
lieutenant in the army opened fire on the Iraqi leader in 
Baghdad earlier this month. The officer appeared to be acting 
alone, he said. The official, who did not wish to be named, also 
confirmed reports which emerged from Baghdad three weeks ago 
about a bomb attack against the presidential convoy. 
  The explosive device had been left in a tractor abandoned by 
the roadside and was detonated as the convoy passed on Dec 28. 
  Last summer between 60 and 300 people were arrested and put 
to death, accused of being involved in an aborted coup attempt. 
Many of those rounded up were senior and trusted figures in the 
regime and came from Saddam's home city of Takrit. 
  According to Iraqi opposition sources, the latest attempt on 
the president's life may have been carried out by an officer who 
was seeking revenge for the death of a member of his family in 
the purge. 

</TEXT>

