<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arab League Official: 12th Round Talks `Final Test' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1701161694 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 1500 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1701161694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ambassador 'Adnan 'Imran, assistant secretary 
general of the Arab League for political affairs, has emphasized 
that the Syrian-U.S. summit in Geneva has achieved a positive 
shift in the Arabs' favor that must be consolidated in the next 
round of talks in Washington. 
  He said that the 12th round [of Arab-Israeli talks] will be 
a 
final test of Israel's commitment to peace and of the United 
States' ability to carry out its responsibilities and 
commitments. This, he added, is directly linked not only to 
security and stability in the Middle East but to the United 
States' future relations with the countries in the region. 
  In statements made today on the outcome of the 
al-Asad-Clinton summit, he said that Syrian President Hafiz 
al-Asad was able to rearrange the Arab-Israeli conflict and link 
all the tracks in an attempt to achieve a comprehensive 
solution, which U.S. President Clinton affirmed at the end of 
the summit. 
  Peace, as viewed by the Syrian president, involves not only 
the Syrian track but the Lebanese and Jordanian tracks and the 
legitimate Palestinian rights. Thus, we can say that the issue 
has regained its balance and comprehensiveness. 

</TEXT>

