<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iranian Envoy to Afghanistan Cited on Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1501070594 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0430 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1501070594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Persian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone report by correspondent Darestani from Islamabad] </F>
  [Text] After meeting with the conflicting sides in 
Afghanistan, the Islamic Republic's special envoy to Afghanistan 
has returned to Peshawar, Pakistan. 
  During his three-day visit to Kabul, Taherian conveyed a 
verbal message from President Hashemi-Rafsanjani to Afghan 
President Borhanoddin Rabbani and handed a written message from 
Foreign Minister Velayati to Afghan Prime Minister Golboddin 
Hekmatyar. He also held talks with Mazari, secretary general of 
the Hezb-e Wahdat [Islamic Unity Party] and the high-ranking 
representative of Afghanistan's national-Islamic movement in 
Kabul. 
  In an interview this morning, he stated that the Islamic 
Republic of Iran is doing its best to bring together the heads 
of the conflicting sides in order to achieve understanding and 
that it is giving attention to consultations with our neighbors 
in this. The Islamic Republic's special envoy to Afghanistan 
added: 
  [Begin Taherian recording] Following the contacts, the 
conflicting sides agreed to name representatives, who will start 
meeting as soon as possible. But it may be too soon yet to make 
any assessment of this. We intend, God willing, to continue our 
efforts aimed at achieving results and we hope that, God 
willing, we will achieve something specific. [end recording] 
  Taherian said in conclusion that in continuation of his 
mission he will start meetings with Pakistani officials today so 
that views can be exchanged between officials of the two 
countries on how to end the battles in Afghanistan and to 
promote understanding among the conflicting sides. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-53711 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes012_p_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-012 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Factions Reject Pakistani Peace Initiative </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1801171794 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 15 Jan 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1801171794 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Afghan Factions Reject Pakistani </F>
Initiative and Escalate Fighting"] 
  [Excerpt] Kabul, London, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- The warring 
Afghan factions yesterday rejected a Pakistani peace initiative 
and pledged to continue the fighting "until complete victory." 
  The aim of the Pakistani initiative, which was supported by 
the United States and Russia, was to make arrangements for an 
unconditional cease-fire to be followed by peace talks in 
Islamabad within one week. 
  A spokesman for 'Abdol Rashid Dostam said that there would 
be 
no cease-fire agreement before interim President Borhanoddin 
Rabbani resigns and leaves the country. 
  Interim Prime Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar, whose Hezb-e 
Eslami Party and Dostam's Uzbek militias are now allies, 
supported Dostam's position. 
  There was no categorical rejection of the Pakistani 
initiative by the opposing side led by former Defense Minister 
Ahmad Shah Mas'ud, but a spokesman for Mas'ud said that Dostam 
would be excluded from any future talks and that Hekmatyar would 
be invited as a faction leader and not as interim prime minister. 
  There was fierce fighting in Kabul yesterday in which 
missiles and aircraft were used. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

