<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Armed Clash Reportedly Follows Brigades' Move </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1801163694 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 15 Jan 94 
pp1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1801163694 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Reports by 'Abdallah Hammudah in Aden and Hammud Munsir in </F>
Sanaa: "Yemeni Exchange of Fire on Former Borders"] 
  [Excerpt] Political sources in more than one Yemeni party 
have revealed that there was an exchange of fire from light and 
medium weapons two days ago between southern and northern 
military units on the old partition borders in the governorates 
of Shabwah and Ma'ribb. 
  In a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT, the sources confirmed 
that the exchange of fire was stopped within hours to avoid an 
eruption of the situation because of the political crisis which 
has prevailed in Yemen for about five months. 
  It is worth noting that these clashes occurred after the 
arrival of three Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] brigades in 
Shabwah from other governorates including Hadramaut. They are 
the 30th Brigade, the Taysir Brigade, and the 'Abbas Brigade. 
They tightened control of the oil area which was a joint area 
between the two Yemens before unity. It was considered "a joint 
investment zone." Oil prospecting and production rights there 
were given to the French company Total which announced the 
discovery of an oilfield last October after the exploratory 
drilling of three wells. 
  While General People's Congress [GPC] sources accused the 
YSP 
of moving these brigades, the YSP claimed that the GPC had moved 
several units from al-Hudaydah to Ta'izz near Aden and 
reinforced its units in the governorates of Ibb and al-Bayda'. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

