<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Speaker Reaffirms Commitment to Unity </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1901111094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 17 Jan 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1901111094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on "exclusive" interview with Shaykh 'Abdallah </F>
Bin-Husayn al-Ahmar, speaker of the Yemeni House of 
Representatives and chairman of the Yemeni Reform Grouping 
Higher Committee, by Hammud Munsir in Sanaa and 'Abdallah 
Hammudah and Lutfi Shatarah in Aden; date not given: "Al-Ahmar: 
We Accept What They Impose for the Sake of Unity"] 
  [Excerpts] Shaykh 'Abdallah Bin-Husayn al-Ahmar, speaker 
of the Yemeni House of Representatives and chairman of the 
Yemeni Reform Grouping [YRG] Higher Committee, has stated that 
"unity is dear to us and we have paid the price for it but now 
they want an additional price." He was referring to the demands 
included in the 18 points submitted by the Yemeni Socialist 
Party [YSP]. He added: "They are imposing things on us; we 
accept, for the sake of unity." 
  This came in an exclusive interview with AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT 
at 
Shaykh al-Ahmar's home in Sanaa in which he said: "Our view is 
that everything possible has been done but there should be 
agreement on the constitutional amendments." He also said that 
the "points are acceptable (in principle), go in stages, and 
could be carried out by the government." He added: "Out of our 
concern for unity we accept everything they impose, which is a 
bitter pill to swallow." 
  Political sources in Aden have confirmed that Yemeni 
Planning 
and Development Minister Dr. 'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani has 
resigned in protest against an order issued by Prime Minister 
Eng. Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas calling for discontinuation of 
the Yemeni population and establishments census. Sources close 
to al-Iryani said that he considered that decision to favor 
partition and division. 
  Out of his concern for Yemeni unity, Shaykh al-Ahmar is 
making efforts as speaker of the House of Representatives which 
is the only unity institution still functioning regularly. He 
stressed that he is by no means acting as YRG leader. He said: 
"Responsibility has made it incumbent upon us to be passive and 
not to say what we believe should be said." 
  In reply to a question about views expressed by political 
observers to the effect that the YSP is exerting pressure "for a 
stable state system but is working for a continuation of the 
state of unrest and anticipation for as long as possible to get 
as many concessions as possible," Shaykh 'Abdallah al-Ahmar 
said: "Why should we preoccupy ourselves with analysis and 
speculation? The situation is clear. That is the position of 
the (YSP) Political Bureau and Central Committee." 
  Shaykh 'Abdallah al-Ahmar emphasized that the decision about 
the state system and whether it should be a parliamentary or 
presidential system "should be a part of the constitutional 
amendments." He added: "We have our own views regarding the 
local councils system which is in harmony with the current 
Constitution, and regarding financial and administrative 
decentralization." 
  On the divisive military movements within the state of 
unity, 
the speaker said: "There have been movements which nobody can 
deny such as the transfer of some units from the eastern areas 
to Shabwah, but there has been no confirmation of other things 
and we hve not heard about them." He reaffirmed the importance 
of preserving unity. He said: "Despite everything, we are 
prepared to come to some understanding with them (the YSP) for 
the sake of unity, which was a precious achievement, dear to us. 
We are prepared to offer many times the sacrifices we have 
already made for its sake." 
  Shaykh al-Ahmar denied that the YRG had "any part in causing 
the crisis." 
  He stressed that "there are no differences within the 
presidency of the House of Representatives. There can be no 
doubt about that. We all work together" because "the House of 
Representatives is the only unity body still functioning, albeit 
with little output." 
  He said that "the Socialist deputies attend and we have had 
no disagreement with them on any measures, because we have not 
reached the point of decision on the measures which should be 
taken and to which the House of Representatives is entitled." 
He said that "the House of Representatives, like other state 
institutions, has been affected by the crisis but we are still 
holding together and there has been no dispute within the 
House." [passage omitted] 
  It should be noted that the prime minister and the ministers 
of defense, oil, transport, and housing, and the deputy prime 
minister for manpower are all in Aden and do not discharge their 
ministerial duties or take part in the cabinet meetings in 
Sanaa. The cabinet holds regular meetings under the 
chairmanship of Dr. Hasan Makki, member of the General Committee 
(Political Bureau) of the General People's Congress [GPC] and 
first deputy prime minister. 
  In reply to a question about the absence of these ministers 
and whether there is justification for withdrawing confidence 
from the cabinet and forming a new cabinet, a YSP source said 
that the reason they have stayed away from Sanaa was the 
discovery of a plan for their assassination. He added that 
senior state officials knew that. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

