<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Geneva Summit Marks `Moment of Truth' for Israel </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1901144294 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 18 Jan 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1901144294 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Salwa al-Ustuwani report: "Damascus Circles Talk About </F>
Conditions for Full Normalization"] 
  [Excerpt] Damascus, Amman, Beirut, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- 
Damascus circles hope that the Syrian-U.S. summit held in Geneva 
the day before yesterday will be "the beginning of a new phase 
that leads to returning the land to its owners and hence full 
normalization through the land-for-peace principle, so that the 
region will move to the stage of economic development and 
prosperity." A senior Syrian official told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT 
that his country's position and concept of a just and 
comprehensive peace were announced very clearly in Geneva, and 
that the moment of truth has come for Israel to respond to the 
voice of peace, which was announced again from Geneva. 
  The Syrian official was speaking after President Hafiz 
al-Asad's return from Geneva the night before last after his 
historic meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton. Tahir 
al-Masri, speaker of the Jordanian House of Representatives, 
said the meeting is as important as the Madrid conference from 
which the peace process was launched. Maybe in this context, 
too, Lebanese President Ilyas al-Hirawi spoke to the Syrian 
president over the telephone to agree to hold a summit in 
Damascus, to be attended from the Lebanese side -- in addition 
to President al-Hirawi -- by Chamber of Deputies Speaker Nabih 
Birri, Prime Minister Rafiq al-Hariri, Foreign Minister Faris 
Buwayz, and Ambassador Suhayl Shammas, head of the peace 
delegation to the negotiations with Israel. 
  A Lebanese presidential source told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that 
President al-Asad has asked Lebanese officials to wait two days, 
to allow him to rest after his journey to and from Geneva. He 
will receive them later. However, the source said that, if 
something happens and delays this Lebanese-Syrian summit, Syrian 
Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' will visit Beirut to brief 
officials on the results of the Geneva summit, and the summit 
would then be held later in Damascus. 
  On the significance of the Geneva summit, the Syrian 
official 
told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that the U.S. Administration's renewal of 
its commitment -- openly and clearly -- and its intention to do 
all it can to achieve a just and comprehensive peace, is another 
reason for the optimism about achieving the desired peace. 
However the official said that this peace is still surrounded 
by caution, because Israel has not yet expressed its intentions 
regarding commitment to this peace. It is still maneuvering, 
claiming it does not understand the peace proposed by Syria. 
  The official said: How can the United States, in particular 
its President, and the world as a whole understand and support 
what Syria has proposed with regard to peace, while Israel still 
has not understood the Syrian view? Does that not indicate that 
Israel is still acting stubbornly by refusing to accept a peace 
based on the known foundations endorsed by the resolutions of 
international legitimacy? 
  The Syrian official pointed out that Syria, which adhered to 
full sovereignty over the Golan, also clearly adheres to a 
complete Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon. This applies 
also to Jerusalem, the West Bank, the Gaza Strip, and the 
Palestinians' rights. This was stressed by President Hafiz 
al-Asad during his talks with President Clinton in Geneva. The 
summit reflected a full U.S. understanding of the Syrian view. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

