<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Samahah on Council of Ministers Session </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1801200494 Beirut Voice of Lebanon in Arabic 1915 GMT 18 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1801200494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Voice of Lebanon </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Information Minister Michel Samahah after the </F>
Council of Ministers session in Beirut on 18 January -- recorded] 
  [Text] The Council of Ministers held an extraordinary 
session this afternoon by invitation from the prime minister. 
The president chaired the session. The president opened the 
session by deeply thanking President Hafiz al-Asad for bearing 
the case of Lebanon in his heart and mind at the summit he held 
with President Clinton in Geneva. The subject of Lebanese 
rights took up a large part of this summit, during which 
President Hafiz al-Asad concentrated on the implementation of 
Resolution 425. This was included in President al-Asad's 
statement after the summit. 
  The president also informed the Council of Ministers of the 
contacts he held after the summit with President Hafiz al-Asad. 
The president told the Council of Ministers that this afternoon 
he received the U.S. ambassador in Lebanon, who conveyed a 
message from President Clinton detailing the discussions during 
the summit regarding Lebanon and the future direction of peace 
negotiations in Washington. President Clinton is trying to make 
1994 the year for establishing peace in the region. 
  The Council of Ministers also learned about the contents of 
the telephone conversation between U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher and the prime minister after the Syrian-U.S. 
summit in Geneva ended. 
  In preparation for the Chamber of Deputies discussions of 
the 
1994 budget on Thursday, the minister of state for financial 
affairs presented to the Council of Ministers the budget for 
1994 with the amendments made by the parliamentary Finance and 
Budget Committee. The Council of Ministers discussed all these 
points and approved the amendments made by the Committee. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

