<H3> <TI>   Clinton Informs Rabin of Access to U.S. `Projects' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1801202594 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1801202594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Gadi Sukenik] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Cabinet ministers are bound 
to rejoice when they are informed of President Clinton's 
message, which was delivered to Prime Minister Rabin on Sunday 
[16 January]. The message says that as of now, Israel may 
participate in U.S. tenders and projects involving the launching 
of space satellites. The license includes access to American 
equipment and expertise. Until now, any such access was denied 
to our hi tech companies. This is a tangible expression of the 
United States' strong commitment to preserving Israel's 
qualitative edge, Clinton wrote in his letter, which was 
delivered by his team of advisers headed by Dennis Ross. 
  It is estimated in Israel that the implementation of this 
decision will create many new jobs, most notably in the Israel 
Aircraft Industries, REFA'EL [Armament Development Authority], 
and the Israel Military Industries. 

</TEXT>

