<H3> <TI>   Syria Reportedly To Halt Support for Terrorists </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1601071394 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 16 Jan 94 p A1 </F>
<F P=103> TA1601071394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from Geneva by Gay Bekhor] </F>
  [Excerpts] Syrian President Hafiz al-Asad may today notify 
U.S. President Bill Clinton that Syria will stop supporting 
"elements operating against the peace process," that is, the 
Palestinian and Lebanese terror organizations. Contacts on this 
Syrian announcement have been held since last night at the 
Intercontinental Hotel in Geneva. This was told to HA'ARETZ by 
a Lebanese diplomat in Geneva. The announcement reportedly will 
be handed over to the Americans today, but will not be 
publicized. 
  According to the Lebanese diplomat, the Syrians have 
prepared 
an initial draft stipulating that they "will suspend or stop 
supporting elements operating against the peace process." The 
Americans, however, are demanding a more detailed and explicit 
commitment, including mentioning Hizballah by name. In return, 
the State Department may strike Syria off the list of terror 
supporting countries. [passage omitted] 
  The Lebanese diplomat estimated that the Syrian-Israeli 
rapprochement will be similar to the Israel-PLO mutual 
recognition, which followed 'Arafat's public renouncement of 
terrorism. The Lebanese diplomat believes this will be the main 
achievement of the summit, which is to be held this morning at 
the Intercontinental Hotel in Geneva. The meeting is scheduled 
to last some three hours. A joint news conference may be held at 
the end of the meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

