<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Presents Work Plan for 1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1701093294 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 17 Jan 94 p A5 </F>
<F P=103> TA1701093294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Aluf Ben] </F>
  [Excerpt] Foreign Ministry Director General Uri Savir 
yesterday presented Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres with the 
ministry's working plan for 1994. The plan for the first time 
sets goals for the ministry's units and Israel's representations 
abroad. The most prominent political goal is the establishment 
of full relations between Israel and Muslim countries: 
Indonesia, Malaysia, Bangladesh, and Pakistan -- in Asia; 
Tanzania, Senegal, and Djibouti -- in Africa; and the North 
African and Gulf countries of the Middle East. The Foreign 
Ministry aspires to establish normalization and economic 
relations even before full diplomatic relations are established. 
  Political sources have said that it is important that ties 
with the large Muslim countries be established before 
negotiations on the future of Jerusalem start. Progress in 
establishing ties with the Muslim and regional countries will 
depend on progress on and the implementation of the agreement 
with the PLO and the peace negotiations on the other tracks. 
  The plan sets two economic goals for the Foreign Ministry: 
Reducing trade deficit between Israel and the European 
countries, and fortifying the spread of Israeli economic 
representatives around the world, with a focus on East Asia. 
Negotiations on drafting the new agreement between Israel and 
the EC will begin next month, according to the mandate the EC 
Council issued in December. 
  The plan urges increasing the incorporation of the private 
sector in economic activity abroad, and calls on Israel's 
representatives abroad to assist in the establishment of ties 
between Israeli and foreign businessmen to give trade a boost. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

