<HT>    "drnes012_s_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-012 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> IRAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Va'ezi: National Security, Regional Stability Linked </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801133994 Tehran IRNA in English 1206 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, Jan. 18, IRNA -- Deputy Foreign Minister for 
Euro-American Affairs Mahmud Va'ezi said on Tuesday that Iran 
saw its national security integrated with the establishment of 
stability and calm in the region. 
  Speaking at the international seminar on the process of 
development in Central Asia and Caucasus, Va'ezi also said the 
Islamic Republic was closely monitoring political, social and 
economic developments in Central Asian and Caucasian republics. 
  It is the duty of all countries to contribute to the 
reconstruction of Central Asian countries, the deputy foreign 
minister said. 
  According to Va'ezi, ethnic disputes, civil war and 
conflicts 
with other countries constitute a major impediment to the 
economic development of Central Asian and Caucasian republics. 
  In order to enable those countries to export their gas and 
oil, the Islamic Republic has allowed them to use Iranian ports 
along the Persian Gulf, he said, adding that "this is very 
important and decisive." 
  He said the republics of Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan and 
Azerbaijan can transport their oil and gas to other countries 
via Iran. 
  The volume of trade between Iran and those countries have 
reached 300 million dollars, Va'ezi said, adding "this is good 
for the beginning." 

</TEXT>

