<F P=100> IRAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paris Embassy Denies Sending Letter Bomb to Sweden </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901095594 Tehran IRNA in English 0714 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1901095594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan. 19, IRNA -- Iran's Embassy here Tuesday 
denied allegations on having sent an explosive letter to an 
Iranian residing in Sweden and termed it "banal propaganda". 
  In a statement the embassy said the allegations are mere 
lies 
fabricated by counterrevolutionary terrorist groups. 
  The embassy also said that futility of the allegations will 
become further clear to all when it is asked how it could be 
possible that the sender of such a letter writes down his 
address on the back of the envelope? 
  The statement stressed that it was time for the French 
public 
opinion to deliberate on the presence of terrorist groups who 
have repeatedly committed terrorist acts in France and abroad. 
  AGENCE FRANCE PRESSE (AFP) in a report from Stockholm Monday 
quoted the city police sources that a 45-year-old Swedish of 
Iranian origin was injured the same day due to the explosion of 
a letter sent to his wife. 
  According to the AFP report police sources declined to 
identify the injured, introduced as an opponent of the Islamic 
Republic of Iran. It also added that they did not have any idea 
about the point of departure and exact type of the explosive. 
However the same sources claimed the letter it was sent from 
the Iranian Embassy in Paris. 

</TEXT>

