<H3> <TI>   Islamabad Proposes Talks Aimed at Plebiscite </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1801141694 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1801141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pakistan has proposed to India that future bilateral 
talks should aim at finalizing the modalities for holding a 
plebiscite to ascertain the wishes of the people of Jammu and 
Kashmir. The proposal was conveyed by the foreign secretary, 
Shaharyar M. Khan, to the Indian high commissioner, Mr. S.K. 
Lambha, in Islamabad today. Pakistan has also asked the Indian 
Government to take visible steps in the Indian-held Kashmir so 
that a propitious climate is created for the peaceful resolution 
of the Jammu and Kashmir dispute. Pakistan has asked the Indian 
Government for an early response to the proposals, which are 
aimed at focussing on essential issues relating to Kashmir and 
to giving a meaningful and purposeful direction to the talks. 
Pakistan's high commissioner to India will hand over the 
proposal to the Indian foreign secretary, Mr. J.N. Dixit, later 
today. 

</TEXT>

