<H3> <TI>   Amnesty for FIS Leaders `Not Ruled Out' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1801154694 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 17 Jan 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM1801154694 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Algeria: Kafi Decides To Live in </F>
Tunisia"] 
  [Excerpt] Algeria -- AL-HAYAH has learned that Algerian 
President 'Ali Kafi has decided to live in Tunisia after leaving 
power on 31 January. 
  Well-informed sources have told AL-HAYAH that secret 
contacts 
have been made at the highest level between Tunisia and Algeria 
to guarantee President Kafi's security and stability after the 
end of the Higher State Council's term. 
  The president's wife had gone to Switzerland to look for a 
place for them to live in, but the president prefers to live in 
an Arab country. 
  A source close to the National Dialogue Commission told 
AL-HAYAH that the commission yesterday proposed to President 
Kafi to issue an amnesty for the "Salvation Front leaders" to 
enable to them to participate in the "National Seminar" 
scheduled for 25 and 26 January. It is not ruled out that the 
president may issue an amnesty including Abassi Madani, leader 
of the Islamic Salvation Front. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

