<DOCNO> FBIS3-53841 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes013yy_94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-014 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security, Civilian Affairs Committees Conclude Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   'Arafat Aide Warns Time Running Out </H4>
<F P=102> NC2001202894 Paris AFP in English 1756 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2001202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Mona Salem] </F>
  [Excerpts] Taba, Egypt, Jan 20 (AFP) -- Israel and the PLO 
agreed to disagree on Thursday [20 January] after another round 
of negotiations that failed to break the stalemate over who 
controls border crossings once Palestinian self-rule is 
launched. [passage omitted] 
  A senior aide to PLO leader Yasir 'Arafat, who was in Cairo 
on Thursday, warned the peace process could run out of steam if 
there was no breakthrough within weeks. 
  "I believe we have a few weeks in front of us and if these 
problems are not resolved in weeks I think the whole Declaration 
of Principles and the process will be in danger," Yasir 
'Abdrabbuh told reporters in the capital. 
  "I don't think they have the luxury of time in order to wait 
for months. They need a quick solution as we do," he said, 
referring to Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres who said 
Wednesday that his country could afford to wait. 
  The chief PLO negotiator, Nabil Sha'th, said the Taba 
meetings had produced "some opening." Although a security deal 
is proving elusive, he has reported progress on the hand-over of 
civilian powers to the Palestinians. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

