<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jordanian Forces Reportedly Prepared To Intervene </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1901170094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 18 Jan 94 
pp1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1901170094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Political Studies Center report: "The Story of the </F>
Dispatch of Jordanian Disengagement Force to Yemen: Force 
Recalled While Airborne After Conversation Between King Husayn 
and al-Bid"] 
  [Excerpt] London -- Informed Arab sources have revealed 
details of the story of the dispatch of Jordanian disengagement 
forces to border areas between the two parts of Yemen to observe 
the withdrawal of the forces of Aden's Yemeni Socialist Party 
[YSP] and Sanaa's General People's Congress [GPC] from the 
borders and to prevent any clashes between them because of the 
tense situation there. 
  The sources said that the idea of sending Jordanian 
disengagement forces was conveyed to Amman by Yemeni Deputy 
Prime Minister Mujahid Abu-Shawarib when he visited the 
Jordanian capital a while back and held talks with King Husayn 
of Jordan on the latest developments in the Yemeni crisis. 
  The sources said they believed that King HUsayn understood 
from Abu-Shawarib that the idea of sending Jordanian forces to 
the border between the two parts of Yemen had the approval of 
Yemeni President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih and Vice President 'Ali 
Salim al-Bid, and that is why he ordered the relevant 
authorities in the Jordanian Army command to prepare these 
forces for immediate departure for specified areas in Yemen. 
  The force, consisting of a number of officers and warrant 
officers, boarded a military aircraft which took off for Sanaa 
but did not complete the journey, returning halfway through the 
flight after receiving orders to do so from the Jordanian 
command. 
  According to the sources, it seems that King Husayn, in a 
telephone conversation with 'Ali Salim al-Bid, discovered that 
the idea of sending Jordanian disengagement forces to the border 
areas was a "northern" idea only, and so he ordered the force to 
return to Amman. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

