<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jibril, Habash on Geneva Summit, Syrian Position </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2001131494 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1200 GMT 20 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2001131494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ahmad Jibril, secretary general of the Popular Front 
for the Liberation of Palestine--General Command has said that 
at the [U.S.-Syrian] Geneva summit, the United States tried to 
neutralize the Syrian stand in order to impose the Gaza-Jericho 
agreement and strike at the alliance opposed to the short-term 
agreement between the PLO and Israel. 
  Dr. George Habash, secretary general of the Popular Front 
for 
the Liberation of Palestine [PFLP], believes that the Geneva 
summit results will not have a negative effect on the existing 
alliance between Syria and the Alliance of Palestinian Forces 
[APF] which is opposed to the Israeli Palestinian agreement. 
  Habash's stand was revealed in an answer to a question by 
Salim Badawi related to the possible effect of the Syrian-U.S. 
summit on the opposition methods adopted by the PFLP: 
  [Begin Habash recording] I do not think so. This is because 
our struggle in the PFLP, and this also applies to Hamas, is 
based on struggle inside the occupied territories. Concerning 
this issue, Syria is still strongly supporting the intifadah. 
Therefore, I do not believe that we are facing a great 
diversion between the APF and Syria. Moreover, we must consider 
that despite the Geneva summit, Syria continues to demand the 
implementation of all UN resolutions, not only with respect to 
the Golan but also with respect to Lebanon, and the occupied 
territories, including Jerusalem. This means that this issue 
will be a long drawn out one, especially since we must take into 
consideration the intransigent Israeli attitude. 
  What was Israel's attitude throughout the summit and in its 
aftermath? Israel's answer was to hold a referendum. I see this 
as a kind of escape from the process on the Israeli track. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

