<DOCNO> FBIS3-53905 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes014yy_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-014 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security, Civilian Affairs Committees Conclude Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Shahaq: Talks on Border Crossings `Stuck' </H4>
<F P=102> TA1901151894 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 1330 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1901151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Major General Amnon Shahaq, head of the Israeli 
delegation to the Taba talks, said a short while ago that the 
negotiations on the border crossings were stuck. Shahaq 
asserted that the disagreements between the parties centered on 
security arrangements at the crossings. Our correspondent 
Netan'el Semrik reports from Taba: 
  [Begin recording] [Semrik] Major General Amnon Shahaq, in 
his first public announcement this week, made it clear that the 
issue of the border crossings remained stuck. This, after an 
initial round of talks at Taba, the subsequent understandings 
reached at Oslo, Paris, and Cairo, and even after two days of 
negotiations at Taba this week. 
  [Shahaq] As for the security issues, we are still stuck on 
the issue of the border crossings. We are currently still 
trying to find ways to achieve maximum understanding and 
agreement; however, there are several matters of principle on 
which we disagree with the Palestinian delegation. We regard 
these issues as crucial to maintain the level of security we 
desire. There are several issues pertaining to the border 
crossings themselves which are tied to security arrangements. 
The disagreements between the two parties focus on these issues. 
  [Semrik] Do you think that the intervention of the prime 
minister and Yasir 'Arafat will be necessary on these issues? 
  [Shahaq] In my opinion, both parties are familiar with each 
other's position on the issue of the border crossings. We know 
what the Palestinians want and they know what we want. We have 
to find a way to agree or else there can be no accord. [end 
recording] 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 1400 GMT on 19 January 
adds that "Major General Shahaq told our correspondent Moti Amir 
that the document detailing the points of agreement and 
disagreement between the two parties will be passed up to higher 
echelons. In the committee on civilian affairs, agreement was 
reached on transferring 25 out of the 35 Civil Administration 
offices to Palestinian control."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

