<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security, Civilian Affairs Committees Conclude Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sha'th: No Agreement Yet on Crossings </H4>
<F P=102> NC2001071394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2245 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2001071394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Taba, 19 Jan (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, 
Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat's political adviser and head 
of the Palestinian delegation to the Gaza-Jericho Committee, has 
stated that the Egyptian role is very important and something 
the Palestinians and the Israelis always want. 
  In a statement today, Dr. Sha'th said 'Arafat will ask 
President Husni Mubarak for Egyptian support for the peace 
process when they meet in Cairo tomorrow. 
  He pointed out that the Palestinian and Israeli delegations 
to the Security Affairs Committee reached no agreement on the 
crossings today. He noted that the Palestinian delegation 
submitted a written proposal setting out the points of agreement 
and disagreement on the crossings so that the two delegations 
would not have to discuss the issue from the beginning every 
time and so that the points of agreement and disagreement could 
be submitted to the political leaders of the two delegations to 
try to resolve them. The Israelis will respond to the 
Palestinian proposal tomorrow. 
  Dr. Sha'th said the Civilian Affairs Committee today 
discussed the water issue, saying that it is a difficult 
problem, particularly with regard to Gaza, requiring a concrete 
solution. 
  He affirmed that the Palestinian delegation submitted no new 
papers or proposals on the crossings in Gaza and Jericho or the 
border points between Egypt and Gaza and between Jordan and 
Jericho. He said the Israeli concept is that the crossings are 
an external security affair. Dr. Sha'th said this is the wrong 
interpretation and if they stick to it, it would be difficult to 
reach an agreement. He affirmed that the security at the 
crossings is a Palestinian and Israeli concern, not only 
Israeli. He explained that the crossings to Gaza and Jericho 
should be treated differently and that Israeli supervision 
should be inconspicuous, because Israel will withdraw from these 
two areas rather than the remaining parts of the West Bank. 
  He noted that Israel still has objections on this issue. And 
it has not agreed to place the crossings under international 
supervision. Dr. Sha'th affirmed that Israel is anxious about 
the results of the Geneva summit between Presidents Clinton and 
al-Asad. He said Israel is afraid that the U.S.-Syrian agreement 
will put pressure on it, pressure that will again steer the 
negotiations toward a comprehensive solution, as UN Security 
Council Resolution 242 called for Israeli withdrawal from all 
the occupied Arab territories, not part of them. The head of 
the Palestinian delegation said that despite the problems and 
obstacles facing the Gaza-Jericho Committee, the talks have not 
reached a stage requiring intervention by the United States as a 
cosponsor of the peace process in the area. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

