<H3> <TI>   Security, Civilian Affairs Committees Conclude Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Joint Document Drafted on Crossings </H4>
<F P=102> TA2001162794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1500 GMT 20 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2001162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Israeli and Palestinian delegations in Taba 
have drafted a joint document on the issue of the border 
crossings which specifies all the points of disagreement between 
the parties. Hasan 'Asfur, deputy head of the Palestinian 
delegation, said that the document will be relayed to the two 
leaderships for perusal. According to 'Asfur, over the weekend 
the PLO leadership will decide whether to change the directives 
given to the delegation and whether the negotiations will resume 
next week on the basis of this document. 
  [Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew at 1400 GMT on 20 January 
carries a live report from Taba by Netan'el Semrik, adding that 
"the points of disagreement remain -- as previously -- the 
issues of symbols and procedures for checking those entering and 
departing the autonomy. The document itself is four-pages long 
and includes several dozens clauses and subclauses dealing with 
the various issues."] 
  Our correspondent Moti Amir reports that the Civilian 
Affairs 
Committee postponed the scheduled discussion regarding the 
establishment of television and radio stations because the 
Palestinian expert did not arrive in Taba. 

</TEXT>

