<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Egypt, Israel Try To Reduce Arms Control Tensions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2001140494 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 20 Jan 94 p A4 </F>
<F P=103> TA2001140494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Aluf Ben] </F>
  [Excerpt] Egypt is trying to reduce the tension with 
Israel that has surfaced in the multilateral arms control talks. 
Nabil Fahmi, an aide to the Egyptian foreign minister and head 
of the Egyptian delegation to the arms control talks, yesterday 
visited Israel for a meeting with David 'Ivri, director general 
of the Defense Ministry and head of the Israeli delegation. 
  In this first-of-its-kind direct meeting between the Israeli 
and Egyptian representatives to the arms control talks, the 
sides were able to attain understandings that will prevent 
unnecessary bickering in the upcoming meeting in Cairo planned 
later this month between all the countries participating in the 
multilateral arms control talks. 
  The controversy between Egypt and Israel has centered on 
Egyptian diplomatic efforts to disarm Israel of its nuclear 
capacity and its demand to raise the nuclear issue in the 
multilateral talks as soon as possible. 
  Israel, on the other hand, demands to start the process by 
implementing confidence-building-measures between the region's 
countries, and to delay the nuclear issue until stable peace 
arrangements are implemented in the area. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

