<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sources Say Clinton `Knew in Advance' of Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2001124894 Tel Aviv HATZOFE in Hebrew 20 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> TA2001124894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HATZOFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by the political correspondent in Jerusalem] </F>
  [Excerpt] Political sources in Jerusalem said yesterday 
that President Clinton knew in advance that Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin would decide on a referendum should a withdrawal 
from the Golan Heights be called for. 
  It appears that Rabin divulged this intention to Clinton 
during their last meeting in Washington. Rabin explained to 
Clinton the difficulties he would face in Israel should he have 
to undertake such a task. Therefore, the U.S. Administration 
was not surprised by the announcement on a referendum. 
  Government ministers say they will raise this issue during 
Sunday's cabinet session, because it is inconceivable that Rabin 
should divulge such a move to Clinton while hiding it from the 
government. At the same time, it is believed that at least one 
minister -- Justice Minister David Liba'i, who has already asked 
for information on Swiss referendum laws -- was apprised of the 
plan. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

