<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spending on Golan To Continue at Same Level </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1901204794 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1901204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Studio report by economic correspondent Gil Tamari followed </F>
by Moti 'Eden video report] 
  [Excerpts] [Tamari] Golan Heights settlers have enjoyed 
massive government investments over the last few years. It 
appears that no harm was done to investments on the Golan 
Heights this year as well. Treasury officials this evening 
confirmed, albeit off the record, that investments will continue 
at the same level as before, although they will not include new 
projects. Our correspondent in the north, Moti 'Eden, reports 
on this issue: 
  [Begin 'Eden recording] The amount of funds to be invested 
on the Golan Heights this year will not fall from that invested 
last year. This includes tourism infrastructure, new factories, 
and the expansion of existing factories. Last year the state 
invested 100 million shekels for development purposes on the 
Golan. This included expanding the Qatzrin industrial zone and 
kibbutzim factories. The industrial output on the Golan in the 
same period was six times higher than the investment, namely 
$200 million. [passage omitted] 
  The government plans to invest the same sum of money which 
was invested last year on the Golan Heights, mainly in industry 
and tourism projects. [passage omitted] 
  Another special budgetary allocation which was not included 
in the 100 million shekels allocated to the Golan last year is 
40 million shekels used by the Construction and Housing Ministry 
for renovating Golan Heights roads. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

