<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll: 61 Percent Against Full Golan Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2101112894 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 21 Jan 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> TA2101112894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [YEDI'OT AHARONOT public opinion poll conducted by the Dahaf </F>
Institute, directed by Dr. Mina Tzemah] 
  [Excerpt] How would you reply if a referendum was held 
today on the question: "Are you for or against full 
withdrawal from the Golan Heights in exchange for full peace 
with Syria and appropriate security arrangements?" 
  For -- 37 percent; against -- 61 percent; no reply -- 2 
percent. 
  How would you reply if the referendum question was: "Are you 
for or against partial withdrawal from the Golan 
Heights in exchange for full peace with Syria and appropriate 
security arrangements?" 
  For -- 62 percent; against -- 36 percent; no reply -- 2 
percent. 
  The poll, which was conducted on 19 and 20 January, included 
565 interviewees constituting a representative sample of the 
entire adult Israeli population. 
  An analysis of the connection between voting patterns for 
the 
incumbent Knesset and on the referendum question on 
full withdrawal from the Golan Heights indicates that 
Labor supporters are almost equally divided between support for 
and opposition to full withdrawal. 
  However, the voting patterns of supporters of other parties 
in the Knesset ballot and the poll were obviously comparable, 
with only a minority "crossing the lines": For instance, only 
12 percent of Likud followers support full withdrawal, and only 
14 percent of Meretz followers oppose it. There is a similarly 
significant majority of full withdrawal opponents among the 
supporters of ultra- Orthodox parties (20 percent for withdrawal 
versus 80 percent against among Agudat Yisra'el supporters; 25 
percent for and 75 percent against among SHAS [Torah Observing 
Sephardim] supporters). 
  With the introduction of the question on partial 
withdrawal, the trends change: Only 19 percent of Labor 
supporters are against it versus 80 percent in favor; partial 
withdrawal garners the support of 39 percent of Likud followers, 
some 50 percent of Tzomet and Moledet followers, and 44 percent 
of the National Religious Party followers. 
  The maximum margin of error in this poll is 4 percent. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

