<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Rejects Proposed Israeli Plebiscite on Golan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2001085794 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 0545 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2001085794 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the press review] </F>
  [Text] Under the headline "The New Israeli Maneuver," 
TISHRIN writes: The secrets behind the Israeli proposal, which 
carries the fingerprints of Yitzhaq Rabin, to hold a plebiscite 
on the future of the Golan Heights are gradually coming to 
light. The proposal aims at allowing Israel to usurp part of 
the Golan Heights. This is totally rejected by Syria. 
  The paper explains that Syria though President al-Asad 
before 
and during the [Geneva] summit stressed that the Golan Heights 
will never be a subject of bargaining and that peace hinges on 
the return of the entire Syrian territory. 
  The paper stresses that Syria is not at all interested in 
the 
plebiscite and that the Israelis have no right to hold a 
plebiscite in an occupied Syrian territory. Such a measure 
marks a flagrant encroachment on international law and the 
charters and resolutions of the United Nations. Israel also has 
no right to use the law of the jungle to annul the facts of 
history and geography and the principles of international law. 
Regardless of how long it lasts, occupation will never annul 
Syria's sovereignty over its territory and the identity of the 
Golan Heights. 
  The paper explains that Israel is resorting to further 
intransigence and maneuvering by proposing the plebiscite. The 
paper notes that the Golan Heights belong to the Syrian people 
and not to the Zionist settlers. They are an inseparable part 
of Syria and, in all cases, the Golan Heights are not 
negotiable, and not a single Syrian will accept to relinquish an 
inch of them. 
  TISHRIN concludes by saying: The world welcomed the outcome 
of the Geneva summit and agreed on the positive, constructive 
Syrian role and Syria's complete response to the requirements of 
peace. Israel, in the meantime, is working on sabotaging what 
was achieved and at hindering the efforts in order to return the 
region to despair and bitterness. Only Israel should be blamed 
for this. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

