<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indian Proposal on Kashmir Border Reviewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1801133394 Islamabad PAKISTAN in Urdu 18 Jan 94 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> BK1801133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PAKISTAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Urdu </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "The Proposal To Deploy UN Forces Along the </F>
Line of Control"] 
  [Text] Citing Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shaharyar Khan, 
the Indian English daily THE HINDU writes that Pakistan has 
expressed cautious reaction over an Indian proposal to convert 
the Line of Control [LOC] in Jammu and Kashmir into a line of 
peace and tranquility and has given the impression that Pakistan 
will be glad to hold direct talks, if this proposal reflects 
India's intention to reduce the forces deployed on the LOC. 
But, if India wants Pakistan to accept the current situation in 
Kashmir as it is, Pakistan is not ready for it. 
  Whenever India accuses Pakistan of interfering in occupied 
Kashmir, Pakistan puts up a proposal to have the LOC under U.N. 
supervision. But, India does not accept it. India also does 
not want the representatives of human rights organizations to 
visit occupied Kashmir and see for themselves the human rights 
violations there. Pakistan has positively responded to every 
positive proposal and will continue to do so. India should have 
the moral courage within itself to accept the proposal to let 
the LOC be supervised by the U.N. forces or the member countries 
of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation. 
Pakistan is also ready to consider the reduction of forces 
along the LOC. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

