<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security, Civilian Affairs Committees Conclude Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Israel Said Demanding `Security Belt' </H4>
<F P=102> TA1901153194 Tel Aviv DAVAR in Hebrew 19 Jan 94 pp 1, 2 </F>
<F P=103> TA1901153194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv DAVAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Moti Bassok and On Levi] </F>
  [Excerpts] Israel is demanding in the Taba talks the 
setting up of a security belt around the Qatif Bloc settlements, 
which would increase the territory to be left under its control 
to 46 square kms. The Palestinians agree to Israeli control 
over an area of 19 to 20 square kms. It was finally agreed 
yesterday that PLO leader Yasir 'Arafat and Foreign Minister 
Shim'on Peres will meet in Oslo on Saturday in a further attempt 
to break the deadlock in the Taba talks. 
  It was learned yesterday that contrary to announcements by 
Israeli spokesmen there is a sharp dispute between Israel and 
the Palestinians on the size of the Israeli autonomy area in the 
Qatif Bloc. Israel is demanding that in addition to the 
territories of the settlements and the areas in between them, it 
will have control of a security belt that would "wrap" the 
settlements from outside. Israel is demanding overall 46 square 
kms. The Palestinians are opposed to this and are agreeing to 
leaving some 19 to 20 square kms with Israel. [passage omitted] 
  The Security Committee in the Taba talks has still not found 
a compromise formula for control of the border crossings. Some 
progress was made in the Civilian Affairs Committee, headed by 
Brigadier General Gadi Zohar. It was decided to set up a single 
dialing area for the autonomy and to frank a Palestinian stamp. 
  Senior sources in the Israeli delegation said last night 
that 
"there would be no Israeli compromise on the crossings issue. 
Israel went a long way toward the Palestinians on that issue and 
we now expect them to show flexibility." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

