<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Baz, PLO's Sha'th on Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2301172294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1255 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2301172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 23 Jan (MENA)--Dr. Usamah al-Baz, Foreign 
Ministry first under secretary and director of the President's 
Office for Political Affairs, said that President Husni Mubarak 
and President 'Arafat today reviewed the PLO-Israeli 
negotiations in Oslo, the progress made in the Taba talks, and 
ways to achieve further progress on a formula to implement the 
Palestinian-Israeli Declaration of Principles. 
  Commenting on the Palestinian-Israeli talks, al-Baz said 
obviously the climate in which the talks are conducted has 
improved and become positive and that agreement between the two 
sides is likely in the next few weeks. 
  For his part, Dr. Nabil Sha'th, head of the Palestinian side 
in the Taba talks, said after his meeting today with Foreign 
Minister 'Amr Musa and Dr. Usamah al-Baz that important talks to 
overcome obstacles delaying an agreement on Gaza and Jericho, 
especially differences on the crossings and Jericho, were held 
after President 'Arafat's visit to Oslo and his meeting with the 
Israeli foreign minister. 
  Sha'th added that President 'Arafat briefed President 
Mubarak 
on developments in Oslo and discussed future steps with him. 
Sha'th said that President Mubarak invited the Palestinian 
delegation to a working breakfast with President 'Arafat. 
Presidents Mubarak and 'Arafat then asked the Palestinian 
delegation to meet with 'Amr Musa and Dr. al-Baz to continue 
discussion of a plan for a joint move to resolve the problems. 
  Sha'th affirmed that Egypt is exerting efforts, as it has 
been since the start of the negotiations, to resolve outstanding 
problems. 
  The head of the Palestinian side on the Gaza-Jericho 
Committee said that the latest talks in Taba saw a serious, 
objective attempt to break the deadlock. He added: We 
submitted a paper in Taba that was the subject of discussion in 
Oslo, and thus, the attempt to break the deadlock began in Taba 
and continued in Oslo and then in Cairo. 
  Sha'th said he will return to Taba after tomorrow, Tuesday, 
to resume negotiations with General Shahaq, who will be briefed 
by then on Shim'on Peres' view of the talks that were held with 
'Arafat in Oslo. He added that talks on the civilian authority 
will be resumed in Taba tomorrow. 
  He said that President 'Arafat will meet Shim'on Peres in 
Davos, Switzerland, on Sunday [30 January] and expressed his 
belief that the Davos meeting will help lead to an agreement 
soon. Sha'th added that no time has yet been fixed for a 
meeting between 'Arafat and Rabin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

