<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Sources' on Minister's Visit to Libya </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2301130894 Abu Dhabi AL-ITTIHAD AL-USBU'I in Arabic 20 Jan 
94 pp 1, 30 </F>

<F P=103> JN2301130894 </F>
<F P=104>  Abu Dhabi AL-ITTIHAD AL-USBU'I </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo -- AL-ITTIHAD AL-USBU'I -- Informed Egyptian 
sources have affirmed that Egyptian Information Minister Safwat 
al-Sharif's recent mission to Libya was to inform Colonel 
Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi that Cairo apologizes that it cannot 
welcome him for talks with President Husni Mubarak before it is 
confirmed that Libya has nothing to do with the disappearance of 
Libyan opposition figure Masnur al-Kikhya, who disappeared in 
Cairo in unclear circumstances. 
  Last week, al-Qadhdhafi again asked to visit Cairo or 
al-Sallum to remove the misunderstanding between his country and 
Egypt because of the al-Khikya incident. 
  In his message, al-Qadhdhafi renewed his offer to mediate 
between Egypt and Sudan and to host an Egyptian-Sudanese summit 
in Tripoli. 
  The Egyptian information minister told him that the Egyptian 
and Sudanese foreign ministers are holding contacts to resolve 
controversial issues between the two countries, and that any 
future summit depends on the success of the expected meeting 
between the two foreign ministers. 
  Safwat al-Sharif also informed Libyan officials that the 
Egyptian Government categorically refuses to deport Libyan 
opposition activists in Cairo because they have not violated the 
terms of political asylum granted to them. Libya had proposed 
that the opposition activists be deported from Cairo to avoid 
any tension their presence might cause to Egyptian-Libyan 
relations. 
  Egypt last week refused to welcome the senior Libyan 
official, al-Khuwaylidi al-Humaydi, who requested to visit Cairo 
during his recent presence in Tunis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

