<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sidqi Addresses Parliament on Corruption </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2301185994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1558 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2301185994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Cairo, 23 Jan (MENA)--Prime Minister Dr. 'Atif 
Sidqi asserted that the government has not and will not keep 
silent about any incident of corruption, no matter who the 
perpetrator. 
  Addressing a People's Assembly session held today to debate 
the report of the committee tasked with replying to the 
government policy statement, Sidqi said every report on 
corruption or deviations from any source, even anonymous ones, 
is passed on for investigation with the knowledge of the 
authorities concerned. 
  He added that people must not be accused without evidence or 
according to mere reports because this is regarded as 
intellectual terrorism. Referring to newspaper reports on 
corruption cases, he said if such corruption happened in any 
society, such a society would be barbaric. 
  Speaking about corruption, Khalid Muhyi-al-Din, opposition 
leader in the People's Assembly, said he did not mean by his 
speech to accuse anyone and that he knows that Prime Minister 
Dr. 'Atif Sidqi is the one who ordered an investigation on 
Madinat al-Nasr's multimillionaire. He added that he knows the 
government, including not only the council of ministers but also 
the administration agency, is opposed to such acts. I do not 
mean to stand up against anyone or accuse anyone without 
evidence, he remarked. 
  Kamal al-Shadhili, minister of state for the People's 
Assembly and consultative council affairs, said corruption is 
not common practice, and that the prime minister has affirmed 
that neither corruption nor deviations will be protected and all 
such cases will be invesitgated. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

