<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister: Country To Turn Toward China </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  EA2101163094 Omdurman National Unity Radio in Arabic 1315 
GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA2101163094 </F>
<F P=104>  Omdurman National Unity Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Husayn Sulayman Abu-Salih has 
stated that Sudan's foreign relations with neighboring countries 
rely on firm principles, which are based on respect for existing 
regimes and borders and noninterference in internal affairs. 
  He pointed out that there were some powers which did not 
approve of the stability of Sudan and which strove to disrupt 
its relations with its neighbors. He said this yesterday when 
he met a Chinese media delegation. 
  The foreign minister pointed out the presence of foreign 
interference, which sought to disrupt good relations with 
fraternal Eritrea. He stressed that there was a need to be wary 
of such plots. 
  During the meeting, Dr. Abu-Salih reviewed Sudan's efforts 
to 
achieve an Arab accord. His excellency appealed to African 
countries to rely on themselves to develop their own 
capabilities. He pointed out that the stands of western 
countries against Sudan came about because of Sudan's 
independent decision-making. He confirmed that Sudan would be 
turning toward the east and China to achieve its independence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

