<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Civilian Affairs Committee Resumes Talks in Taba </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2401100594 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0915 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2401100594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Taba, 24 Jan (MENA)--In Taba this morning 
Palestinian and Israeli negotiators began a third week of talks 
in connection with the Gaza-Jericho agreement. 
  The negotiations resumed at 1030 when the Civilian Affairs 
Committee stemming from the Gaza-Jericho Committee met under 
lawyer Jamil al-Tarifi on the Palestinian side and Gadi Zohar, 
the Israeli official in charge of the civil administration in 
the occupied West Bank. 
  Al-Tarifi told MENA that the committee will discuss issues 
related to the transfer of civilian authority from Israel to the 
Palestinians. He said that this week's negotiations will focus 
on communications -- including radio, television, postal 
services, electricity -- and the Palestinian authority's right 
to enact legislation and handle town planning, civil 
registration, and travel documents. He added that the issue of 
water will be discussed not this week but next week. 
  MENA learned that Radwan Abu-'Ayyash, head of the radio and 
television corporation, and Engineer Amin 'Ulayyan have joined 
the Palestinian delegation negotiating the transfer of civilian 
authority because the setting up of a Palestinian radio and 
television station will be discussed. 
  The Palestinian negotiator stressed that there was progress 
during the past two weeks of negotiations on civilian issues 
when the two sides reached agreement on issuing identity cards 
and issues of residence, protected nature reserves, and public 
works. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

