<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Abd-al-Majid Attends Agriculture Meeting in Syria </TI></H3>
<H4>   Interviewed on Mideast Market, Reconciliation </H4>
<F P=102> NC2401093194 Cairo Voice of the Arabs in Arabic 0610 GMT 24 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2401093194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Voice of the Arabs </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Arab League Secretary General Dr. </F>
'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid, in Damascus, by Ashraf 'Abd-al-'Aziz in 
Cairo; date not given; from the "Dialogue From Afar" program -- 
recorded] 
  [Text] ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Welcome to our program. 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] Thank you. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Could you tell us about the talks you held 
with various officials in Damascus? 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] Actually, I came to Damascus to attend the 
annual session of the Arab agriculture ministers, which is 
sponsored by the Arab Agricultural Development Organization. 
During the meetings we looked into the agricultural strategy of 
the Arab World in light of developments in the region. In my 
opening speech, as well as in the talks I held, I emphasized the 
importance of peace in the region as well as of confronting the 
economic blocs that are being formed in other parts of the 
world. It is essential that the Arab World takes a clear 
position on these blocs, particularly following the signing of 
GATT and other economic agreements. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Let us talk for a while about the Arab 
economic strategy that the agriculture ministers are discussing. 
What is the Arab vision of this strategy, particularly in view 
of the current regional and international developments? 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] The Arab vision has several parts. The Arabs 
need to maintain their food and water security. The Arabs 
should also find a way to confront the economic blocs that have 
sprung up in other parts of the world, particularly following 
the signing of GATT, an agreement that will affect [trade in] 
agricultural crops. 
  This topic....[pauses] The timing of the current meeting in 
Damascus was good. GATT was signed in December. The official 
signing ceremony will take place in April and then the agreement 
will be ratified. 
  Among the topics discussed during the meeting was ending the 
subsidies to agricultural products and farmers. This topic was 
given much thought in many countries during the GATT talks and 
the earlier talks in Uruguay. The Arab ministers are focusing 
on these issues. We hope that, by the end of the meeting in 
Damascus, a fuller picture will emerge of the Arab agricultural 
strategy. Such a strategy is needed to protect the Arab food 
and water supply, for it represents a part of Arab national 
security 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Let us have a look at the other challenges 
facing the Arab World, such as the issue of water. 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] The issue of water, as I said, is one of the 
challenges preoccupying the Arab public in the entire region. 
Of course, this and other topics will be discussed again at the 
coming meeting of the Economic and Social Council, which will be 
held in Cairo in February, God willing. The Arab League Council 
will also review these topics during its regular session in 
March. 
  The timing of the meeting here was good, as well as the 
preparations. There is no doubt that the meeting and the 
discussions will help create a joint Arab position. This is all 
I have got to say on this subject. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] How do you see the future of Arab economic 
cooperation, especially in light of what is being touted as the 
possible establishment of a Middle East [trade] area? 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] I have commented before and in length on the 
matter of the Middle East market. First of all, we have to 
discuss it with each other and see where we stand before we 
begin talking about a Middle East market involving non-Arabs. 
But, for starters, we should not be afraid of the prospect of a 
Middle East market. We should get our act together and see 
where our interests lie. I think that nothing can be imposed on 
Arab countries. These countries are sovereign and will not 
accept anything that contradicts their regional and pan-Arab 
interests. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] There is a question on the minds of all 
Arabs, private citizens as well as officials. What is happening 
on your initiative to achieve Arab reconciliation? How far has 
this initiative gone? 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] Hopefully, it is still alive and well. The 
responses I have received so far have been limited. Actually, I 
have received only 13 responses from the heads of states. But I 
believe that there is a possibility for further consultations 
about it. In the end, we will have to agree that it is in our 
interest to clear the Arab atmosphere and restore Arab 
solidarity, for this will strengthen the entire Arab World. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] How do you see these efforts proceeding? Is 
there hope for genuine reconciliation among the Arab brothers? 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] I see some factors leading us somewhat 
toward 
clearing the Arab atmosphere. What is needed is more efforts. 
I am confident that the Arab World can exert these efforts. 
Arab reconciliation should be based on frankness. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Thank you. 
  ['Abd-al-Majid] You are welcome. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

