<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister on Accord Document, Reservations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2201193294 London MBC Television in Arabic 1800 GMT 22 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2201193294 </F>
<F P=104>  London MBC Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] has voiced optimism 
regarding the document drawn up by the National Dialogue 
Committee to solve the dispute between leaders in north and 
south Yemen. The YSP Central Committee declared that the 
document, which was prepared with the help of various political 
forces, is a document of national consensus. 
  It appears, however, that implementing the agreement's 
clauses will run into some difficulties particularly in light of 
a reply message sent by Prime Minister Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas 
to President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih accusing him of squandering 
public funds. Another difficulty is that the leaders in the 
south have stressed that their return to take up their posts in 
Sanaa hinges on the removal of the causes that made them leave 
the city in the first place. 
  Our correspondent Tawfiq Jazulit interviewed Prime Minister 
al-'Attas and prepared the following report: 
  [Begin recording] [Jazulit] The YSP Central Committee held 
an 
extraordinary session in Aden today under the chairmanship of 
Yemeni Vice President and YSP Secretary General 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid. YSP deputies in the Yemeni parliament and the 
secretaries of YSP branches in Yemeni governorates attended the 
session. 
  [Al-'Attas] The YSP Central Committee has devoted 
considerable attention to this document. This meeting was held 
specifically to consider this document in a manner appropriate 
to its importance and to enable every YSP member to carry out 
his duty in implementing it. 
  [Jazulit] Therefore the YSP will sign the Pledge and Accord 
Document, isn't that right? 
  [Al-'Attas] The YSP will sign the document, as the National 
Dialogue Committee did, during a major ceremony, the date and 
venue of which will be agreed upon. This will happen when a 
special committee completes clause number seven which deals 
specifically with security arrangements and when guarantees are 
drawn up that the agreement will be implemented. 
  [Jazulit] What powers will be given to the vice president in 
the amended constitution? 
  [Al-'Attas] The vice president will assist the president and 
will carry out the president's tasks when he is abroad, ill, or 
cannot carry out his duties for any other reason. He will also 
have the power to supervise the prime minister's work in 
connection with local government affairs. 
  [Jazulit] Is the crisis in unified Yemen over or do some 
reservations persist? 
  [Al-'Attas] To tell the truth, some parties to the dialogue 
-- specifically parties within the coalition -- have some 
reservations about the document. This casts doubt on the 
prospects for implementing it. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

