<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Amman Reportedly Likely To Host Salih-al-Bid Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2301084794 Amman AL-DUSTUR in Arabic 23 Jan 94 pp 1, 31 </F>
<F P=103> JN2301084794 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-DUSTUR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Salah al-Qallab from Aden] </F>
  [Excerpts] It has become almost certain that the 
anticipated meeting between Yemeni President 'Ali 'Abdallah 
Salih and Yemeni Vice President 'Ali Salim al-Bid will be held 
in Amman. 
  A source at the Follow-Up Committee, which is making 
arrangements for this meeting, and which comprises several 
leading national and partisan figures, has informed AL-DUSTUR 
that the committee's preference is to see the ceremony for 
signing the document of understanding take place in the 
Jordanian capital under the auspices of His Majesty King Husayn 
and the Jordanian people. 
  The source added that since the security situation precludes 
the holding of such a meeting in Yemen, all parties prefer to 
see the reconciliation meeting between the Yemeni president and 
his deputy take place in Amman, given the role His Majesty King 
Husayn has played to achieve reconciliation, and also due to the 
balanced Jordanian position toward the Yemeni crisis from the 
outset. 
  The source indicated that invitations for this ceremony will 
be extended to some Arab leaders, foremost among which will be 
Omani Sultan Qabus Bin-Sa'id, Palestinian President Yasir 
'Arafat, representatives of several foreign countries, and Arab 
League representatives after coordination is effected between 
the Yemeni Government and the Jordanian Government. 
  It is clear that the Follow-Up Committee charged with making 
arrangements for this meeting, which comprises Shaykh Sinan 
Abu-Luhum, Brigadier General Mujahid Abu-Shawarib, 'Abdallah 
al-Anisi, Dr. 'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani, Culture Minister Jarallah 
'Umar, and Ahmad Jabir 'Afif, has agreed to hold the 
reconciliation meeting in Jordan in light of the contacts held 
within the past four days. 
  Given the current security situation, heightened tension, 
and 
several complicated circumstances, it has become very clear that 
it is impossible to hold the reconciliation meeting anywhere in 
Yemen. In this regard, several senior Yemeni officials said that 
President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih refuses to see the meeting take 
place in Hadramawt. Similarly, Yemeni Vice President 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid is opposed to signing the reconciliation document in 
Sanaa. 
  Several Yemeni officials said that the security situation 
and 
mutual mistrust will prompt any official who will have to attend 
this meeting to bring with him a large number of guards and 
escorts to protect him, a number that could exceed 
5,000--something which would make it impossible to get the 
situation under control, and which might consequently cause a 
security disaster. [passage omitted] 
  It is to be recalled that the Yemeni vice president has 
welcomed the holding of this meeting in Amman. A senior 
official of the Yemeni Socialist Party has said: In case it is 
found to be impossible to hold the reconciliation meeting on 
Yemeni territory, our first preference is to see it held in 
Amman. (passage omitted] 
  AL-DUSTUR also learned that France expressed a willingness 
to 
host the reconciliation meeting on its territory. However, 
Yemeni officials said that they prefer to see it held on Arab 
territory if it is found to be impossible to hold it on Yemeni 
territory. They added that they prefer to see it held in Amman 
if an agreement is reached on holding it in an Arab capital. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

